98
00:07:55,920 --> 00:08:01,600
that you teach your team to deal with hardship 
and to take a punch. So what are some of those  

99
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:05,760
things? What are some of the things that you 
teach your team and help them develop a skill?

100
00:08:05,760 --> 00:08:09,920
So at its core, when I say take a punch, 
what I mean is you're going to run into  

101
00:08:09,920 --> 00:08:15,120
situations where something has gone wrong. 
Maybe you have misstepped. Maybe you are  

102
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:19,520
just hearing someone speak critically 
about your work. Whatever it might be,  

103
00:08:19,520 --> 00:08:24,400
you're going to feel like you have taken a punch.
It's a very physical feeling. And I think as  

104
00:08:24,400 --> 00:08:30,720
managers, you spend a lot of time teaching 
your team how to be successful. You want to  

105
00:08:30,720 --> 00:08:35,120
prepare them to maximize the chances of good 
outcome. But if you don't also prepare them  

106
00:08:35,120 --> 00:08:41,040
for what happens when that outcome isn't as 
good, you're going to run into some problems. 

107
00:08:41,040 --> 00:08:47,600
And so when I think about how to take a punch, 
what I say to my team is if they come to me and  

108
00:08:47,600 --> 00:08:52,400
they're upset because something has happened, 
maybe they said something in a meeting that  

109
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:57,440
wasn't received well, or again, they're hearing 
somebody else talk about them in some way,  

110
00:08:57,440 --> 00:09:02,080
whatever it is, I try to focus them 
less around whatever happened and how  

111
00:09:02,080 --> 00:09:06,880
you litigate another person's impression of you 
based on something that has already happened,  

112
00:09:06,880 --> 00:09:12,480
and more on what is the action that you can take 
next to counter program the narrative that you  

113
00:09:12,480 --> 00:09:18,080
are afraid that this other person has of you.
And I think the counter program piece is really  

114
00:09:18,080 --> 00:09:22,880
important. Because whenever we feel our 
egos injured, I think it's very natural  

115
00:09:22,880 --> 00:09:27,040
for all of us to say like, "Well, that's 
not fair. I want to correct the record."  

116
00:09:27,040 --> 00:09:31,440
When you do that, I think more than often, 
more often than not, you come off as just  

117
00:09:31,440 --> 00:09:36,800
looking defensive and you start obsessing over 
things that you don't actually have control over,  

118
00:09:36,800 --> 00:09:40,960
which is what another person thinks of you. You 
don't even necessarily have that information. 

119
00:09:40,960 --> 00:09:46,240
And so I always ask myself in these moments, 
what is one thing that I can do, small,  

120
00:09:46,240 --> 00:09:52,560
that will demonstrate the opposite of what 
I'm afraid this person thinks of me? And so  

121
00:09:52,560 --> 00:09:57,760
I'll give you an example of this. I was in 
a meeting a while ago, and we were talking  

122
00:09:57,760 --> 00:10:03,200
about different things that we wanted to start 
tracking in the Whoop Journal. And our chief  

123
00:10:03,200 --> 00:10:09,360
technology officer suggested ketamine tracking.
And I thought she was making a joke and I laughed,  

124
00:10:09,360 --> 00:10:14,480
and she looked at me very seriously and was 
like, "This isn't funny, Hilary. This is a  

125
00:10:14,480 --> 00:10:21,840
serious issue for a lot of people, and it's an 
emerging problem in some cases. And I think we  

126
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:25,520
should take it seriously. I think there's a 
lot of value we could provide here." And I  

127
00:10:25,520 --> 00:10:31,520
was completely humiliated. Humiliated because 
I actually take this stuff really seriously. I  

128
00:10:31,520 --> 00:10:36,480
take addiction really seriously. I have a ton 
of empathy for people who struggle with it. 

129
00:10:36,480 --> 00:10:41,440
And I also think of myself as somebody who 
embraces new ideas and wants to be on the  

130
00:10:41,440 --> 00:10:47,840
forefront and would never laugh off something 
that seems like a fringe issue that's I think  

131
00:10:47,840 --> 00:10:55,280
becoming actually more and more a big part of 
what's happening today. And so I realized that  

132
00:10:55,280 --> 00:11:01,360
in that moment I was having that reaction because 
of the feeling that it gave me about who I am as  

133
00:11:01,360 --> 00:11:06,640
a person, and I became so worried that this 
other person had the wrong impression of me. 

134
00:11:06,640 --> 00:11:10,960
And I wanted to follow up with her after and 
say, "Let me explain myself. Let me explain  

135
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:17,280
why I didn't mean that," or whatever it is. But 
as I said, I think usually you're fighting a  

136
00:11:17,280 --> 00:11:21,360
losing battle when you're trying to do that, 
and it draws attention to the thing that you  

137
00:11:21,360 --> 00:11:25,920
did poorly. And you don't really want to draw 
more attention to it. You want to move on,  

138
00:11:25,920 --> 00:11:31,760
take action, move forward. And so I thought about, 
well, what am I afraid that she thinks of me? 

139
00:11:31,760 --> 00:11:35,760
I'm afraid that she thinks that maybe I 
don't take some of these health issues  

140
00:11:35,760 --> 00:11:43,920
seriously. I'm afraid she thinks that maybe 
I'm somebody who laughs off emerging trends.  

141
00:11:43,920 --> 00:11:49,680
And so I thought about what's something that I 
could do to demonstrate the opposite of that? 

142
00:11:49,680 --> 00:11:56,800
And I did some research very, very quickly on 
what are some emerging public health concerns  

143
00:11:56,800 --> 00:12:00,880
that people really aren't talking about that 
would be interesting to track? And I found  

144
00:12:00,880 --> 00:12:04,960
some interesting research about sports betting, 
and especially young people in sports betting,  

145
00:12:04,960 --> 00:12:08,800
and it's becoming this thing that a lot of 
public health experts are very worried about. 

146
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:14,240
And so I very quickly just sent her a note 
that said, "Wanted to build on this idea you  

147
00:12:14,240 --> 00:12:20,800
had today. I really liked that idea, by the way. 
I saw this article, I saw this research about  

148
00:12:20,800 --> 00:12:24,240
this other emerging thing, sports betting, 
and I think it'd be really interesting for  

149
00:12:24,240 --> 00:12:29,360
us to start tracking that because we could maybe 
draw some correlations between people stress. We  

150
00:12:29,360 --> 00:12:33,280
have a stress monitor in Whoop. We can track their 
stress. We could draw interesting correlations  

151
00:12:33,280 --> 00:12:38,640
between betting behaviors and stress levels."
And so that's all I did. It took me five,  

152
00:12:38,640 --> 00:12:44,640
10 minutes total. But I think it's a great example 
of showing this idea of counter-program that  

153
00:12:44,640 --> 00:12:49,680
narrative, don't fight about the narrative. And so 
when I teach this to my team, I'm always doing the  

154
00:12:49,680 --> 00:12:55,440
same thing. They come to me. They seem agitated 
about something and I say to them, "It seems like  

155
00:12:55,440 --> 00:12:59,440
this is really bothering you. What's going on in 
your head? What are you afraid of? What are you  

156
00:12:59,440 --> 00:13:04,160
worried about?" And often it will emerge, "I'm 
worried that this other person thinks I'm bad at  

157
00:13:04,160 --> 00:13:08,880
my job. I'm worried that this person thinks I'm 
an idiot," whatever it is. And I challenge that.  

158
00:13:08,880 --> 00:13:12,240
I think this is really important for managers 
too to challenge this negative thinking when  

159
00:13:12,240 --> 00:13:17,520
you see it happen and not just validate it and 
allow them to go down these negative spirals. 

160
00:13:17,520 --> 00:13:21,920
I challenge it and I say, "First of all, 
I don't think there's evidence for that.  

161
00:13:21,920 --> 00:13:28,560
Is there evidence for that? And even if there 
is, it doesn't really matter. What's something  

162
00:13:28,560 --> 00:13:32,240
that you could do to show them that it's 
not true because you know it's not true?" 

163
00:13:32,240 --> 00:13:36,720
And I think giving people that power to 
focus on the next step they can take and  

164
00:13:36,720 --> 00:13:41,760
the action that they can take that helps them 
feel more secure in their identity in who they  

165
00:13:41,760 --> 00:13:45,680
are because their action demonstrates that, it 
just gets them out of that negative thinking  

166
00:13:45,680 --> 00:13:52,160
and it gets them through that trough of despair 
that comes after you feel like you took a punch.

167
00:13:52,160 --> 00:13:58,800
So the idea here is when you're afraid somebody 
that matters in your career thinks ill of you,  

168
00:13:58,800 --> 00:14:02,880
of something that you did, of you're not 
good at something or you think something  

169
00:14:02,880 --> 00:14:07,440
that they're not happy about, this is a 
version of getting punched basically is  

170
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:11,360
you just feeling like someone thinks you're 
not doing a great job. And so the tactic here  

171
00:14:11,360 --> 00:14:16,320
is how to change their mind almost about 
you and give you something tangible to do.

172
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:17,520
Exactly.

173
00:14:17,520 --> 00:14:20,960
Okay. And so the question to ask, and 
I wrote this down as you were talking,  

174
00:14:20,960 --> 00:14:24,080
is, and this is what you ask of your 
reports, what is the one thing that  

175
00:14:24,080 --> 00:14:28,720
you can do that demonstrates the opposite of 
what you think this person thinks about you?

176
00:14:28,720 --> 00:14:34,480
Exactly. This comes up all the time. 
There will be narratives that emerge,  

177
00:14:34,480 --> 00:14:39,200
some are good, some are bad, about you and 
your career. And I think especially when  

178
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:44,080
people get to a place where they're putting 
themselves out there more, they're talking  

179
00:14:44,080 --> 00:14:49,520
in more presentations, they're talking in more 
meetings, it's very natural for them to become  

180
00:14:49,520 --> 00:14:54,160
concerned with the perception themselves.
And it is scary because it feels like something,  

181
00:14:54,160 --> 00:14:57,840
as I said, you don't have control 
over. And so exactly. If instead of  

182
00:14:57,840 --> 00:15:01,760
focusing people around what do these people 
think of me, you focus them around, well,  

183
00:15:01,760 --> 00:15:07,360
what are you going to do next to demonstrate that 
you are the person that you know yourself to be,  

184
00:15:07,360 --> 00:15:12,400
I think that can just be incredibly effective 
at giving people more of a sense of agency.

185
00:15:12,400 --> 00:15:18,000
I guess talk about the balance of I'm just 
going to prove everyone wrong against what  

186
00:15:18,000 --> 00:15:22,720
they think versus here's who I am and 
I know this is me and this person is  

187
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:27,040
mistaken. And instead of debating them, 
I'm going to show them who I am. Just not  

188
00:15:27,040 --> 00:15:30,800
overstressing about everyone thinking 
things about you in different ways.

189
00:15:30,800 --> 00:15:36,720
There is some value I think in having a little bit 
of a chip on your shoulder. You see that people  

190
00:15:36,720 --> 00:15:41,200
who are really successful, they do have a little 
bit of like, "I'm going to prove them wrong." And  

191
00:15:41,200 --> 00:15:45,440
so I don't want to say that you shouldn't think 
about it at all or you shouldn't care. Of course,  

192
00:15:45,440 --> 00:15:50,560
it's natural to care, and of course, it's fine 
to care, but I do want to just help my team  

193
00:15:50,560 --> 00:15:56,160
build this habit of doing the things that you 
know to be right and having conviction in that. 

194
00:15:57,120 --> 00:16:03,680
Being open to learning along the way and 
calibrating as you go, but not becoming  

195
00:16:03,680 --> 00:16:09,360
overly concerned with your fears of what other 
people are going to think of you. Because I think  

196
00:16:09,360 --> 00:16:16,720
especially for otherwise really thoughtful, 
really the people who are hard on themselves,  

197
00:16:16,720 --> 00:16:21,360
I think that that just holds them back 
from being the person that they can be.

198
00:16:21,360 --> 00:16:26,560
So a key part of this is, this is going to 
help you stop just spiraling on thinking  

199
00:16:26,560 --> 00:16:30,800
about what they think about you and gives 
you something to do that will change that.  

200
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:34,400
And then the other key point here is don't 
try to convince them otherwise. You're not  

201
00:16:34,400 --> 00:16:40,320
going to go to your manager like, "Oh, I 
really think ketamine therapy and addiction  

202
00:16:40,320 --> 00:16:44,960
is really important, and I didn't mean to 
say it this way," and that kind of thing.

203
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:49,520
I'm not interested in litigating the things that 
happened already when we can move forward. And  

204
00:16:49,520 --> 00:16:54,560
I'm certainly not interested in litigating what 
another person thinks about a thing that happened.  

205
00:16:55,440 --> 00:16:59,760
I feel like I've spent so much time talking 
to people in meetings, whatever it is,  

206
00:16:59,760 --> 00:17:06,080
where it's just this ruminating on something 
that has already happened. It's very anxious  

207
00:17:06,080 --> 00:17:13,840
thinking pattern, I think, and people can 
just get stuck in it. And so let them do it. 

208
00:17:15,840 --> 00:17:23,360
It's like when you get bad feedback or critical 
feedback and you naturally have this reaction of,  

209
00:17:23,360 --> 00:17:27,840
"Oh, well, that's not fair because they 
don't understand. I actually have numbers  

210
00:17:27,840 --> 00:17:33,280
I have to deliver on, or I only had 10 minutes 
to do this, so of course, it wasn't perfect."  

211
00:17:33,280 --> 00:17:42,640
You naturally come up with these reasons why you 
are actually not wrong, and that's fine. I don't  

212
00:17:42,640 --> 00:17:47,200
want to say you should feel bad for doing that.
Let yourself have the pity party, let yourself  

213
00:17:47,200 --> 00:17:52,400
feel those things, but then you got to move on 
as quickly as possible because those feelings,  

214
00:17:52,400 --> 00:17:58,720
they actually do tend to spiral and get worse 
if you're not actively working against them.

215
00:17:58,720 --> 00:18:04,880
Oftentimes these sorts of lessons come from 
the person experiencing this themselves. Is  

216
00:18:04,880 --> 00:18:08,160
this something that you dealt with when 
you're starting your career or even now?

217
00:18:08,160 --> 00:18:15,760
Oh, absolutely, 100%. And I think it is more 
than just my career, but just my general  

218
00:18:15,760 --> 00:18:22,880
mental health and my life. A lot of where this 
comes from is a concept in cognitive behavioral  

219
00:18:22,880 --> 00:18:27,280
therapy called behavioral activation. 
And in my former job, I was working for  

220
00:18:27,280 --> 00:18:33,120
a company called Big Health and we make digital 
therapeutics. So those are mobile apps that have  

221
00:18:33,120 --> 00:18:38,720
been clinically validated to treat behavioral 
conditions like insomnia, depression, anxiety. 

222
00:18:38,720 --> 00:18:42,640
And I was working on a new depression 
therapeutic, and so went very deep on this  

223
00:18:42,640 --> 00:18:47,680
and was working with a really wonderful clinical 
team full of clinical psychologists who helped me  

224
00:18:47,680 --> 00:18:52,240
understand the techniques that therapists 
use when they are working with people who  

225
00:18:52,240 --> 00:18:57,760
have depression. And so much of depression 
is characterized by these negative thinking  

226
00:18:57,760 --> 00:19:05,040
patterns and this feeling that I feel bad and I 
just need to wait until I feel better, and then  

227
00:19:05,040 --> 00:19:12,560
I'll start doing the things that are good for me.
I don't feel like responding to this text,  

228
00:19:12,560 --> 00:19:16,480
so I'm just not going to do it, but I'll respond 
when I feel better. I don't feel like working out,  

229
00:19:16,480 --> 00:19:22,880
so I'm not going to do it, but I'll do it when I 
feel better. And the truth is that doesn't go away  

230
00:19:22,880 --> 00:19:33,360
on its own, especially if you have depression. 
Again, the idea of behavioral activation is  

231
00:19:33,360 --> 00:19:37,760
you have to identify these actions that 
you can take that will reverse that  

232
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:45,360
negative spiral and will improve your mood.
And so the misconception is I'll feel better  

233
00:19:45,360 --> 00:19:50,400
and then I'll act. And the thing that therapists 
try to teach people, they're working with them in  

234
00:19:50,400 --> 00:19:56,160
therapy is I will act and then I will feel better. 
But acting is hard if you are in the furrows of  

235
00:19:56,160 --> 00:20:01,280
depression. And so easier said than done. And 
a lot of the work is in how you help people  

236
00:20:01,280 --> 00:20:07,280
identify specific actions that they can 
take that will reliably lift their mood. 

237
00:20:07,280 --> 00:20:12,160
I mean, I have a list of myself. I've got a 
list on my phone of my behavioral activations,  

238
00:20:12,160 --> 00:20:17,920
and it's things that I know I can do if I start 
feeling like the walls are closing around me,  

239
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:24,240
if I feel myself getting sucked into 
very low mood or negative thinking,  

240
00:20:24,240 --> 00:20:29,280
or whatever it is. You can see how effective 
that is at just getting you out of there versus  

241
00:20:29,280 --> 00:20:35,360
the instinct to just go and lay in bed and feel 
bad for yourself, which I understand very well. 

242
00:20:35,360 --> 00:20:40,800
And so understanding that concept, which is 
at its core a therapeutic concept used in  

243
00:20:40,800 --> 00:20:48,320
cognitive behavioral therapy, but it changed 
how I see the entire world and how I see,  

244
00:20:48,320 --> 00:20:54,960
especially as a manager, the ways that people 
on my team think and behave and how easy it is  

245
00:20:54,960 --> 00:21:01,440
to get stuck in some of these downward spirals 
that you really need to actively push back on.  

246
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:05,840
And as a manager, I want to help them do that.
I want to help them, A, see that, see the ways  

247
00:21:05,840 --> 00:21:12,320
they are in some ways sabotaging themselves, 
getting in their own ways with whatever is  

248
00:21:12,320 --> 00:21:18,400
going on in their head. And then I want to help 
them counter-program it in themselves. And also,  

249
00:21:18,400 --> 00:21:22,800
as I said, counter-program the things that 
you are worried about out there as well.

250
00:21:22,800 --> 00:21:26,800
So interesting. So the core of 
this technique is what's an action,  

251
00:21:26,800 --> 00:21:28,000
and you said this, it could be very small.

252
00:21:28,000 --> 00:21:29,040
Very small.

253
00:21:29,040 --> 00:21:33,760
That you can take that in this case 
shows someone else you're not who  

254
00:21:33,760 --> 00:21:37,040
they think you are. You're worried 
they think about you in a certain  

255
00:21:37,040 --> 00:21:40,720
way and you want to take an action 
that helps them see you're not that.

256
00:21:40,720 --> 00:21:45,840
So yes, that's the taking the punch concept. The 
behavioral activation could be anything. It can be  

257
00:21:45,840 --> 00:21:51,120
picking up a piece of laundry off of the chair and 
putting it away, and that's just enough to get you  

258
00:21:51,120 --> 00:21:57,680
out of the downward thing you're in. So behavioral 
activation just conceptually is, how are you  

259
00:21:57,680 --> 00:22:03,440
taking action to reverse the downward feeling 
or the negative feeling that you're feeling?  

260
00:22:03,440 --> 00:22:10,080
And then the take a punch concept is that applied 
in the context of I'm in a working environment. 

261
00:22:10,080 --> 00:22:14,880
I am very conscious of how I'm being perceived by 
other people. That's causing me a great deal of  

262
00:22:14,880 --> 00:22:20,960
stress. I think especially for product people who 
are... So much of their self identity is wrapped  

263
00:22:20,960 --> 00:22:26,480
up in having the answers, being competent, 
getting things done. And so many of them  

264
00:22:26,480 --> 00:22:30,400
have been people who have been really good at 
that for most of their careers, which is how  

265
00:22:30,400 --> 00:22:34,560
they got into these jobs in the first place.
I think that can be an extremely stressful  

266
00:22:34,560 --> 00:22:41,600
thing for them. That in many cases can be the 
driver of burnout and the driver of I can't  

267
00:22:41,600 --> 00:22:48,000
really handle the stress of this job anymore. 
And so I think the take a punch concept is more  

268
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:53,760
just applied to that specific problem of I'm 
struggling at work and I'm struggling largely  

269
00:22:53,760 --> 00:22:58,880
because of my perceptions of other people and 
I want to feel more agency in that situation.

270
00:22:58,880 --> 00:23:07,120
This is so cool. On the idea of the specific take 
a punch concept, what kind of impact have you seen  

271
00:23:07,120 --> 00:23:13,120
this have on people's mood and careers? 
How big a deal is this specific tactic?

272
00:23:13,120 --> 00:23:18,240
Well, I think it's a big deal on two levels. 
One, it's a big deal because it can help you  

273
00:23:18,240 --> 00:23:25,200
in a crisis or a minor crisis. But I actually 
think it's a bigger deal because I see so many  

274
00:23:25,200 --> 00:23:30,640
people who don't put themselves out there because 
they're afraid of how it's going to go. And so I  

275
00:23:30,640 --> 00:23:37,200
think of the classic example of I'm often trying 
to encourage people to speak up in meetings more,  

276
00:23:37,760 --> 00:23:43,600
to practice the skill of how you move a 
conversation forward in a way that can contribute  

277
00:23:43,600 --> 00:23:49,680
value, both because doing so I think is important 
because nobody wants to be in bad meetings,  

278
00:23:49,680 --> 00:23:54,240
but also because it will help with your career.
This is how you get on people's radar as somebody  

279
00:23:54,240 --> 00:23:57,840
who's like, "Oh, that person's got great ideas, 
thinks about things the right way," whatever it  

280
00:23:57,840 --> 00:24:05,280
is. I think it's one of these things that I talk 
to people about it and they are interested in  

281
00:24:05,280 --> 00:24:09,280
coming to the meeting and hearing about 
these big decisions are getting made,  

282
00:24:09,280 --> 00:24:13,440
but they just want to sit there and observe. 
And I'm like, first of all, every additional  

283
00:24:13,440 --> 00:24:18,240
person in a meeting has a cost, because every 
additional person in a meeting makes the people  

284
00:24:18,240 --> 00:24:22,880
in that meeting less candid than they would have 
been if there were fewer people in that meeting. 

285
00:24:22,880 --> 00:24:29,520
And so one key piece of a meeting is you usually 
have a problem you're trying to solve collectively  

286
00:24:29,520 --> 00:24:34,320
as a group. And it's really hard to do that 
if people are being overly cautious about what  

287
00:24:34,320 --> 00:24:40,880
they're saying because there's too many people 
in there. So when I tell people this, I'm like,  

288
00:24:40,880 --> 00:24:46,480
"It's really important that you earn your place 
in this meeting and let's work on how to do that." 

289
00:24:46,480 --> 00:24:52,080
And the core piece of that is you've got 
to say stuff that's valuable. And people  

290
00:24:52,080 --> 00:24:56,160
always come up with all these excuses for why 
they can't do it. And one thing I've learned  

291
00:24:56,160 --> 00:25:01,120
is that I think people are really good at coming 
up with very rational sounding reasons to not do  

292
00:25:01,120 --> 00:25:07,200
things that just make them uncomfortable. But in 
their head they're like, "Oh no, I'm too junior. 

293
00:25:07,200 --> 00:25:11,120
Nobody wants to hear what I have to say. 
Or everyone was already thinking it. Or  

294
00:25:12,000 --> 00:25:15,600
I like to process things internally. And by 
the time I say them, the conversation moved  

295
00:25:15,600 --> 00:25:22,240
on," whatever it is. So much of that skill, 
it's like a communication skill at its core,  

296
00:25:22,240 --> 00:25:28,240
it's just how to express yourself verbally, 
but so much of the blocker of that is I think  

297
00:25:28,240 --> 00:25:33,760
fear. Fear of saying the wrong thing.
Fear of looking stupid. Fear of just the  

298
00:25:33,760 --> 00:25:38,320
discomfort of everyone in a room turning 
and looking at you as you're trying to  

299
00:25:38,320 --> 00:25:43,440
formulate a half-baked thought. And so if 
you can help people be less afraid of that,  

300
00:25:43,440 --> 00:25:48,400
that's 90% of the challenge of actually 
improving some of these skills. And so I  

301
00:25:48,400 --> 00:25:53,760
think when you give people the skills of taking 
a punch, you are helping them feel less afraid  

302
00:25:53,760 --> 00:25:57,680
of getting the punch in the first place. 
And that's why I think it's so important.

303
00:25:57,680 --> 00:26:02,480
That's profound, the second order effect of 
the skill. There's something you mentioned  

304
00:26:02,480 --> 00:26:06,080
when we were chatting earlier that 
stuck with me with this idea that too  

305
00:26:06,080 --> 00:26:10,480
many PMs and too many people are playing 
on easy mode and not trying hard things.

306
00:26:10,480 --> 00:26:12,080
Uh-oh. Maybe we'll get ourselves in trouble here.

307
00:26:12,080 --> 00:26:15,440
Okay, let's do it. Say more.

308
00:26:15,440 --> 00:26:21,280
Oh, I think this is my hot take. You hear 
people talking about craft and taste and product  

309
00:26:21,280 --> 00:26:27,920
management, and it's all very wonderful. And I'm 
totally on board. I love it. I'm a sucker for  

310
00:26:27,920 --> 00:26:35,360
that kind of thing, but I'm like, well, if you are 
really in it just for pure love of the game, you  

311
00:26:35,360 --> 00:26:41,920
just love product management, why are you building 
products for people exactly like you who have all  

312
00:26:41,920 --> 00:26:50,080
your exact same at a company that sells to other 
companies that doesn't worry about pricing? 

313
00:26:50,080 --> 00:26:53,040
There's no real... I mean, I don't 
want to act like I think this is easy,  

314
00:26:53,040 --> 00:27:02,320
to be clear. But in the grand scheme of things, 
I wish that the people who have this pure love  

315
00:27:02,320 --> 00:27:06,640
of product management and have this pure love 
of building things that you would see more of  

316
00:27:06,640 --> 00:27:12,880
that applied to building for low income people, 
building for social services, things like that,  

317
00:27:12,880 --> 00:27:18,000
that really, really need that kind of work.
And I think there's a level of prestige  

318
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:23,760
obviously associated with working in certain 
companies, and you get less of that in other  

319
00:27:23,760 --> 00:27:28,720
industries. And so people would naturally 
gravitate toward that. I totally get it. I  

320
00:27:28,720 --> 00:27:34,720
totally get it. You get paid better. No real 
judgment from me. I wish I saw more, but I  

321
00:27:34,720 --> 00:27:37,600
wish that you would see more people. And I'll 
say this, I know there's a lot of you out there. 

322
00:27:37,600 --> 00:27:41,280
I know there's a ton of people out there 
doing really, really important work in really,  

323
00:27:41,280 --> 00:27:47,040
really hard spaces, and I see you and 
I appreciate it and shout out to you.

324
00:27:47,040 --> 00:27:51,360
Awesome. Okay, I'm glad you shared that. 
Thank you. I think this will resonate with  

325
00:27:51,360 --> 00:27:58,240
a lot of people. I want to move on to another 
trait/habits/skill that you are good at and help  

326
00:27:58,240 --> 00:28:04,160
people learn, which is being very transparent 
in what's happening within the organization,  

327
00:28:04,160 --> 00:28:07,440
within your thinking. You almost help 
people think the way you think and see  

328
00:28:07,440 --> 00:28:10,880
the way you think so that they can operate 
at a higher level. Just talk about that,  

329
00:28:10,880 --> 00:28:12,960
what that looks like and why that's important.

330
00:28:12,960 --> 00:28:18,560
It's interesting, I think another thing I hear a 
lot of people complain about in organizations is  

331
00:28:18,560 --> 00:28:24,480
the why do 10 people have to sign off on this 
email before I send it kind of problem. And  

332
00:28:24,480 --> 00:28:31,360
I think the answer to that is because those 10 
people all have different information, different  

333
00:28:31,360 --> 00:28:39,360
context, and in many cases, completely different 
working models for how the CEO of the company and  

334
00:28:39,360 --> 00:28:45,200
other strategic leaders in the company think.
And it makes things super inefficient. I think  

335
00:28:45,200 --> 00:28:48,480
people will often say like, "Oh, it's 
a process problem." It's not a process  

336
00:28:48,480 --> 00:28:52,960
problem. It's not approval problem. I think it's 
a transparency and it's communication problem,  

337
00:28:52,960 --> 00:28:57,520
like downward communication, outward 
communication. And what I mean by that is  

338
00:28:59,440 --> 00:29:01,899
when I think about artifact-based communication, 
so reading a strategy document for...

339
00:29:01,899 --> 00:29:04,640
About artifact-based communication. So reading 
a strategy document, for example. Everyone at  

340
00:29:04,640 --> 00:29:09,520
the company reads the strategy document. Great. 
Everyone is working from the same idea of what  

341
00:29:09,520 --> 00:29:14,240
the strategy is. But then things change, right? 
Especially if you're working in a really dynamic  

342
00:29:14,240 --> 00:29:19,840
space, new competitive threats emerge, new 
opportunities emerge all the time. This is  

343
00:29:19,840 --> 00:29:23,520
especially true now with AI. Obviously everyone 
is lighting their strategies on fire and trying  

344
00:29:23,520 --> 00:29:31,760
to figure out the best way to sort of transform 
their organization. And so if the way that you  

345
00:29:31,760 --> 00:29:35,760
understand what's going on at the company is from 
reading a document that was written six months  

346
00:29:35,760 --> 00:29:41,280
ago, you're going to be working from outdated 
information and you're not going to be able to  

347
00:29:41,280 --> 00:29:47,520
think and respond to new things that happen.
And so what is much more helpful than  

348
00:29:47,520 --> 00:29:53,440
understanding what your CEO thinks is, I think 
understanding how your CEO thinks. And that goes  

349
00:29:53,440 --> 00:29:58,320
for all sorts of levels of the company. I want 
to understand how all the strategic leaders at  

350
00:29:58,320 --> 00:30:03,760
my company think, and I want my team to understand 
how I think. And when I feel confident that people  

351
00:30:03,760 --> 00:30:10,080
on my team understand how I think, I don't need to 
read their emails, I don't need to approve things.  

352
00:30:10,080 --> 00:30:14,560
The times where I feel like I need to do that is 
because I'm working with people where I'm like, I  

353
00:30:14,560 --> 00:30:19,360
don't have confidence that these people understand 
how I think, or I don't have confidence that they  

354
00:30:19,360 --> 00:30:27,040
understand how this email or whatever it is, is 
going to be received by this important person. 

355
00:30:28,080 --> 00:30:35,040
And so I try to teach that to my team. And 
the way that I do that is a few ways. First,  

356
00:30:35,040 --> 00:30:40,880
I'm in meetings with people, important people 
at the company. So I'm constantly hearing the  

357
00:30:40,880 --> 00:30:45,360
things that they're saying and paying attention 
to sort of the note behind the note. Why do I  

358
00:30:45,360 --> 00:30:49,520
think they're saying this? What insight do they 
have that they're bringing to this conversation  

359
00:30:49,520 --> 00:30:56,320
that might not be obvious? And I try to make an 
effort every week. I don't always do it, but I  

360
00:30:56,320 --> 00:31:02,400
try to send my team just a quick rundown in Slack 
of, "Here are the most important conversations or  

361
00:31:02,400 --> 00:31:07,120
the most interesting conversations I had this 
week. Here's what that person said verbatim." 

362
00:31:07,120 --> 00:31:11,760
Again, I write a lot of notes so I've 
got it. If you've got a transcriber,  

363
00:31:11,760 --> 00:31:17,200
maybe that'll help you. "And here's what I 
interpret that as. Here's why I think they  

364
00:31:17,200 --> 00:31:20,800
say that. Here's where I think that's coming from 
and here's what I'm going to do differently as a  

365
00:31:20,800 --> 00:31:25,120
result." And these aren't long. And sometimes if 
I don't have time, I'll just, in a team meeting,  

366
00:31:25,120 --> 00:31:28,320
I'll literally just go through my notes 
from the week and sort of voiceover stuff  

367
00:31:28,320 --> 00:31:35,200
and editorialize it as I go. And over time, I 
think my team has a pretty good sense of what  

368
00:31:35,200 --> 00:31:41,360
people are saying and how to think about the 
thinking behind it and how this person thinks,  

369
00:31:41,360 --> 00:31:46,480
how this person thinks and how I think. And 
I think when you get an entire organization  

370
00:31:46,480 --> 00:31:54,160
working that way where everyone's working from 
the same models of what the CEO thinks matters,  

371
00:31:54,160 --> 00:32:00,080
what level of risk tolerance the company has, 
things like that, then you can actually start  

372
00:32:00,080 --> 00:32:04,160
to move much, much faster and communication 
becomes much, much, much less painful.

373
00:32:04,160 --> 00:32:09,840
So the tactic here is to help your teams 
kind of build a mental model of everyone  

374
00:32:09,840 --> 00:32:14,160
in the company that matters so that it's... 
The way you put it almost is when they're  

375
00:32:14,160 --> 00:32:17,600
emailing them or asking for something, they 
already know how they're going to respond. Is  

376
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:22,160
they're an example you could share of something 
like this, of just something a person at Whoop  

377
00:32:22,160 --> 00:32:25,520
of how they think? I don't know, maybe you 
could keep it anonymous just to make this a  

378
00:32:25,520 --> 00:32:29,680
little reel of the kind of mental model 
you might want to build around someone.

379
00:32:29,680 --> 00:32:39,200
So our CEO, Will, is somebody who obsesses 
over pixels in a way that is challenging to  

380
00:32:39,200 --> 00:32:45,760
get things through design review, but I think 
results in a product that is a thousand times  

381
00:32:45,760 --> 00:32:54,320
better than it would be if he were accepting of 
small excuses here and there for, "Oh, well this,  

382
00:32:54,320 --> 00:32:58,480
we had to cut scope here. We couldn't quite 
do what they wanted here." He sets a high bar  

383
00:32:58,480 --> 00:33:05,200
and he holds it and he doesn't compromise. And I 
think this can sometimes get misconstrued, and I  

384
00:33:05,200 --> 00:33:13,680
think a lot of people might think that he just 
wants maximal scope on everything. And I think  

385
00:33:13,680 --> 00:33:21,360
that is a misunderstanding of what he cares about.
We often get feedback from him that's like, "This  

386
00:33:21,360 --> 00:33:25,600
doesn't feel like the future and everything that 
we're building needs to feel like the future."  

387
00:33:25,600 --> 00:33:30,320
A lot of people hear that and they're kind of 
like, "Oh gosh, we're never going to get this  

388
00:33:30,320 --> 00:33:35,840
thing done on time. We can't make any sort of 
sacrifices to scope or anything like that." But  

389
00:33:35,840 --> 00:33:42,560
when I hear that, what I hear is more that we have 
this AI coach in the product, we have all this  

390
00:33:42,560 --> 00:33:47,680
amazing data in the product. We're tracking every 
single one of your heartbeats and we're pulling at  

391
00:33:47,680 --> 00:33:56,560
all this other data and we have every screen is a 
moment to show that to people in a way that feels  

392
00:33:56,560 --> 00:34:01,040
like something that has never existed before.
And there are small ways to do that,  

393
00:34:01,040 --> 00:34:06,560
right? It's like how you pull in. If you're 
explaining a concept like VO2 Max, which is a  

394
00:34:06,560 --> 00:34:11,600
measure of your cardiovascular health, you can 
explain that to people with static content or  

395
00:34:11,600 --> 00:34:18,080
you can explain that to people by bringing their 
data into the method of explanation that you're  

396
00:34:18,080 --> 00:34:21,440
using. You can make it really conversational 
because you're using this AI coach. You can  

397
00:34:21,440 --> 00:34:26,880
make it feel more like you're talking to a 
person and a person who by the way has all  

398
00:34:26,880 --> 00:34:31,600
the data about you, which doesn't exist today.
Your doctor doesn't have that, your coach doesn't  

399
00:34:31,600 --> 00:34:35,680
have that. And that's not like, "Oh gosh, we've 
got to blow up the scope on this thing and make  

400
00:34:35,680 --> 00:34:40,720
it a hundred X as big." But it's finding these 
little touches to say, "Wow, that was really  

401
00:34:40,720 --> 00:34:45,520
magical, that was really thoughtful and this 
feels like the future. This feels like I'm very  

402
00:34:45,520 --> 00:34:53,600
conscious of the fact that this product knows so 
much about me and is able to sort out the signal  

403
00:34:53,600 --> 00:34:59,440
from the noise on that in these really small and 
elegant ways." And so for something like that,  

404
00:34:59,440 --> 00:35:03,040
I would get that feedback in design review or 
I'd hear that in a design review and maybe one  

405
00:35:03,040 --> 00:35:07,200
of my PMs would be in that design review.
And so I bring that to the team. And I  

406
00:35:07,200 --> 00:35:10,320
hear of things like that in a few different 
design reviews. So I bring those back to the  

407
00:35:10,320 --> 00:35:15,120
team and I'm like, "I've noticed that recently we 
are consistently getting this type of feedback.  

408
00:35:15,120 --> 00:35:20,160
Here's why I think it's really important to 
Will, because I think he's really focused on  

409
00:35:20,160 --> 00:35:27,360
building the health company of the future. And I 
don't want you all to think that this just means  

410
00:35:27,360 --> 00:35:32,240
we have to just throw AI at everything and we 
have to just throw maximum scope at everything. 

411
00:35:32,240 --> 00:35:41,520
I think the key is understanding on the matrix of 
cost and effort for impact, what are those high  

412
00:35:41,520 --> 00:35:48,080
impact but low cost ways that we can just find 
and sprinkle through the experience and really  

413
00:35:48,080 --> 00:35:52,160
try to make that magical?" So I'm connecting the 
dots for my team. Right? I'm saying, "You weren't  

414
00:35:52,160 --> 00:35:57,200
in all these meetings, but I saw it. Here's what 
I heard. Here's my interpretation of what I heard,  

415
00:35:57,200 --> 00:36:01,280
and here's how I'm thinking about how this other 
person thinks about it. And so as a result,  

416
00:36:01,920 --> 00:36:06,320
here are some things that I think we can 
do across our product going forward."

417
00:36:06,320 --> 00:36:11,600
Essentially these are principles, values, or 
tenets per person of what matters to them.

418
00:36:11,600 --> 00:36:11,920
Exactly.

419
00:36:11,920 --> 00:36:15,120
So for Nick it's, "This needs to feel 
like we're living in the future." It  

420
00:36:15,120 --> 00:36:17,760
can't just be like another heartbeat dragging out.

421
00:36:17,760 --> 00:36:18,880
Yeah. Yeah.

422
00:36:18,880 --> 00:36:23,440
This is so cool. And there's so many 
trickle-down benefit to this. One is  

423
00:36:23,440 --> 00:36:26,880
people feel like they're aware of what's 
happening. That's one of the most common,  

424
00:36:26,880 --> 00:36:29,200
I think, piece of feedback people 
have with big companies. Like,  

425
00:36:29,200 --> 00:36:32,000
"I don't know what's happening." So there's 
so much visibility to all the secretive stuff  

426
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:36,080
happening in the meetings. "I don't know what 
people are deciding my fates and all these  

427
00:36:36,080 --> 00:36:40,160
discussions." So I think just even knowing 
that you're sharing all this is so powerful.

428
00:36:40,160 --> 00:36:46,240
Well, and on that note, when I approach these 
conversations, I always try to think of them as,  

429
00:36:47,600 --> 00:36:50,560
even if I don't agree with the feedback, 
if I don't agree with the decision,  

430
00:36:50,560 --> 00:36:54,960
what is the insight that I'm missing? 
How am I wrong about this? In ways like,  

431
00:36:54,960 --> 00:36:58,480
what would be true for this other person to 
be right? And I'll go through that thought  

432
00:36:58,480 --> 00:37:03,680
exercise and I might not get to the other side 
and agree with it. I might still think I'm right  

433
00:37:03,680 --> 00:37:10,240
or whatever. But oftentimes it forcing myself to 
think that way forces me to think about how this  

434
00:37:10,240 --> 00:37:13,920
other person thinks it. And if I do that enough, 
I will be like, "Oh, this makes sense. I think  

435
00:37:13,920 --> 00:37:18,240
this makes sense if. I think this makes sense 
if, and oh, maybe this other thing is true." 

436
00:37:18,240 --> 00:37:21,360
And I think when I hear the people, the people who 
are like, "I don't know what's going on with this  

437
00:37:21,360 --> 00:37:26,160
company," I think they do the opposite. I think 
they look for reasons to disagree and they look  

438
00:37:26,160 --> 00:37:30,720
for holes to poke in, "Well, this decision 
doesn't make any sense because I came up  

439
00:37:30,720 --> 00:37:33,600
with something that might be wrong about it." 
And I think that's another thing, by the way,  

440
00:37:33,600 --> 00:37:38,640
in terms of just sort of helping your team have 
the emotional maturity to exist and thrive in  

441
00:37:38,640 --> 00:37:44,400
an organization is helping them think that way, 
helping them understand you have a point of view. 

442
00:37:44,400 --> 00:37:50,000
Your point of view is important, but on some 
level, you do kind of have to have respect for  

443
00:37:50,000 --> 00:37:54,880
these other points of view and have the humility 
to think that maybe they're onto something that  

444
00:37:54,880 --> 00:38:00,080
you're not onto. And it's amazing how much you 
can learn into it without having to have all the  

445
00:38:00,080 --> 00:38:04,720
facts just by doing that. If you're like, "Well, 
this person's behavior makes sense in a situation  

446
00:38:04,720 --> 00:38:10,000
where X, Y, and Z is happening," oftentimes 
you'll find that X, Y and Z is happening.

447
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:12,560
I'm glad you went there. I wanted to 
actually follow this thread, which is  

448
00:38:12,560 --> 00:38:16,400
kind of a different direction, but I think a 
lot of people are always struggling with this  

449
00:38:16,400 --> 00:38:21,680
as a leader. When your leader disagree, it does 
say something that you completely disagree with,  

450
00:38:21,680 --> 00:38:26,160
but you still need to represent that as, 
"Here's the thing we're doing." But you  

451
00:38:26,160 --> 00:38:29,920
don't want to be like, "Oh, just because Nick 
said so." Because you lose power as a leader.  

452
00:38:30,960 --> 00:38:34,320
Is there something you've learned about 
how to do that well when your leader tells  

453
00:38:34,320 --> 00:38:39,200
you to do something you disagree with and 
you still need to get your team to do it.

454
00:38:39,200 --> 00:38:46,480
First, I do try to go through the what if 
I'm wrong exercise. I think a lot of people  

455
00:38:46,480 --> 00:38:52,720
just sort of expect that if you ask somebody a 
open-ended question like, "Why are we doing this?"  

456
00:38:52,720 --> 00:38:56,880
You're going to get a straightforward answer. And 
oftentimes the answer is not straightforward for  

457
00:38:56,880 --> 00:39:03,440
various reasons. Maybe there's confidentiality 
reasons, maybe there's just somebody is acting  

458
00:39:03,440 --> 00:39:10,080
on a hunch, but that hunch is informed by years 
or decades of reps of developing judgment, and  

459
00:39:10,080 --> 00:39:14,640
they're probably really onto something. And it's 
not just this kind of arbitrary gut feeling. But  

460
00:39:14,640 --> 00:39:21,120
whatever it is, I really try to get to the bottom 
of, let me really make sure that I have done my  

461
00:39:21,120 --> 00:39:25,600
best to understand this person's point of view.
And I have some sort of tools for doing that,  

462
00:39:25,600 --> 00:39:32,240
which I can also talk about. But if I've done 
that, and I still disagree, I'm relatively candid  

463
00:39:32,240 --> 00:39:38,240
about that, but candid in a way where it's still 
respectful. I think what you want to avoid is a  

464
00:39:38,240 --> 00:39:44,480
situation where as a manager you're like, "Ah, I 
have no control. This sucks. This decision is so  

465
00:39:44,480 --> 00:39:51,040
stupid, but that's a job, so we have to do it." 
Obviously that's not going to set your team up  

466
00:39:51,040 --> 00:39:54,880
for success or make anybody happy about it, but 
you do hear that, you do see that happening. And  

467
00:39:54,880 --> 00:40:00,240
so I think what I try to do in those situations is 
separate out my opinion from it, from the, " Well,  

468
00:40:00,240 --> 00:40:04,000
what is the insight that makes it make sense 
to this person" and explain their rationale. 

469
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:09,280
Even if I'm comfortable saying, "I don't 
necessarily think this isn't how I would  

470
00:40:09,280 --> 00:40:14,480
do it," or "I don't even really agree with 
how they're thinking about it, but from  

471
00:40:14,480 --> 00:40:20,080
their point of view, from their perspective, 
their professional experience, whatever it is,  

472
00:40:20,080 --> 00:40:25,360
I could see how this makes sense. And they 
might be right. I don't think they're right,  

473
00:40:25,360 --> 00:40:30,880
but they might be. Let's find out. We're not going 
to find out if we are all squabbling about whether  

474
00:40:30,880 --> 00:40:35,760
this is a good idea the whole time. The only way 
we're going to find out is if we give it the best  

475
00:40:35,760 --> 00:40:41,760
shot that we have and try to do it. And if we're 
wrong, that happens sometimes and we try again."

476
00:40:41,760 --> 00:40:46,640
I like that this comes back to your mental model 
orientation of, "Here's their mental model,  

477
00:40:46,640 --> 00:40:50,480
here's what their experience has been like, 
here's how they see the world, the trends,  

478
00:40:50,480 --> 00:40:55,360
and then this is why they think the way they 
think." And so instead of encouraging your team  

479
00:40:55,360 --> 00:41:00,000
or yourself even to be like, "No, no, you're wrong 
here." It's more, "Okay, here's their data set,  

480
00:41:00,000 --> 00:41:03,360
let's try this, and this will inform that 
data set and maybe change their mind."

481
00:41:03,360 --> 00:41:06,880
Yeah. Because I think in product, I like 
to joke, there's no right answers. Right?  

482
00:41:06,880 --> 00:41:11,200
There's only wrong answers, and you're just 
trying to execute well on the least wrong  

483
00:41:11,200 --> 00:41:17,760
answer that's available to you. And so I think 
it is the sort of reasonable people can disagree  

484
00:41:17,760 --> 00:41:23,360
about this stuff at all of this is what I 
think, and this is how I would approach it.  

485
00:41:23,360 --> 00:41:27,520
I think this is what they think and I think 
this is why they would approach it this way. 

486
00:41:27,520 --> 00:41:34,080
And again, the only chance we have of succeeding 
is not being torn apart on that. And so at the  

487
00:41:34,080 --> 00:41:39,600
end of the day, if it's not a obviously terrible 
answer, and sometimes even if it isn't obviously  

488
00:41:39,600 --> 00:41:46,160
terrible answer, you're still more likely to 
succeed if you just sort of reorient yourself  

489
00:41:46,160 --> 00:41:50,240
around a world where it's not a terrible answer 
and then just try to will that into existence.

490
00:41:50,240 --> 00:41:53,200
You said that you have some tools to 
help you understand someone's point  

491
00:41:53,200 --> 00:41:56,560
of view. I can't help but ask more about that.

492
00:41:56,560 --> 00:42:01,600
I talk about what I like to call the magic 
questions, but the thing about magic questions is  

493
00:42:01,600 --> 00:42:05,440
they're not actually questions, they're statements 
and they end with, "Do you agree?" Or "Is that  

494
00:42:05,440 --> 00:42:12,480
right?" And so I have found this, the most helpful 
way for kind of trying to understand a person's  

495
00:42:12,480 --> 00:42:18,640
mental model is to just put facts in front 
of them and see what they say no to and what  

496
00:42:18,640 --> 00:42:22,240
they say yes to. And then if you can get them to 
explain, great. And if they're good communicators,  

497
00:42:22,240 --> 00:42:28,080
they often can, but if they're not, you don't have 
to let that stop you view. And so I mean, I'll do  

498
00:42:28,080 --> 00:42:34,000
this even just as an example in a non-leadership 
context with if I'm working with legal teams or  

499
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:39,840
compliance teams or things like that, they're 
often working from a literal set of rules. Right? 

500
00:42:39,840 --> 00:42:48,720
There are laws, there are regulations, and you are 
trying to understand if we were to take this path,  

501
00:42:48,720 --> 00:42:54,480
would that be okay? Would that not be okay? 
And sometimes that's not straightforward.  

502
00:42:55,200 --> 00:43:03,440
Sometimes there's regulatory areas that are up 
to interpretation. And so when I first started  

503
00:43:03,440 --> 00:43:08,640
working in a regulated space, I would find this 
kind of frustrating and confusing because I would  

504
00:43:08,640 --> 00:43:14,400
say, "Can you just give me the rule so I can 
understand what's right and what's left of it?"  

505
00:43:14,400 --> 00:43:17,600
And they'd be like, "Oh, well, it depends. 
It depends, it depends." And so I learned  

506
00:43:17,600 --> 00:43:22,560
that if I kind of flip that and approached 
that, "Well, what if we did X, Y, and Z? 

507
00:43:22,560 --> 00:43:27,520
What if this is what it looked like? What if this 
is what the copy said? Would that be okay?" No,  

508
00:43:27,520 --> 00:43:33,120
yes. If no, why? If yes, why? And so I'm sort 
of teasing out the mental model rather than  

509
00:43:33,120 --> 00:43:36,560
asking them to explain it to me. And this is 
what I tell my team all the time to do this  

510
00:43:36,560 --> 00:43:41,040
to me. When they come to me and they say, 
"Well, what do you think I should do?" Or  

511
00:43:41,760 --> 00:43:47,760
"What could I have done differently?" I'll 
say, "Rephrase that as 'Tell me what you  

512
00:43:47,760 --> 00:43:53,200
think you could have done differently.' And 
then ask me if I agree." And when I do this,  

513
00:43:53,200 --> 00:43:58,080
I think it has a few benefits. One, it helps 
them kind of calibrate their judgment over time. 

514
00:43:58,080 --> 00:44:02,000
So they're actually forcing themselves to 
make this assertion. And then they're kind  

515
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:08,080
of calibrating how close that was to how I would 
think about it, which will get you much faster,  

516
00:44:08,080 --> 00:44:12,560
much further than just asking open-ended questions 
and getting the answer. And then the second part  

517
00:44:12,560 --> 00:44:18,000
of it is they don't become reliant on me for 
answering these questions. I think that's kind of  

518
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:23,680
a trap that a lot of managers fall into is people 
come to you with questions, you want to help them,  

519
00:44:23,680 --> 00:44:27,360
you answer the question, and then you find that 
they come to you with all their questions and  

520
00:44:27,360 --> 00:44:31,040
you're kind of like, "Yeah, you got to solve some 
of these on your own." So again, I think the magic  

521
00:44:31,040 --> 00:44:37,760
questions to me, is that right? Do you agree? 
And anytime you find yourself tempted to ask an  

522
00:44:37,760 --> 00:44:43,360
open-ended question to somebody whose brain you're 
trying to understand, stop yourself and say,  

523
00:44:43,360 --> 00:44:47,280
"Let me just say that. Let me say as a statement 
what I think," and then try to calibrate based on  

524
00:44:47,280 --> 00:44:51,760
their reaction. And I think that's the fastest 
way to understand how another person thinks.

525
00:44:51,760 --> 00:44:57,280
It makes me think about a lot of people, it could 
come across as it's a weird manipulative way of  

526
00:44:57,280 --> 00:45:02,240
asking someone stuff, but it turns out that 
we're not good at really knowing what we think  

527
00:45:02,240 --> 00:45:06,160
or know a lot of times. And you need someone 
almost to interview you in a really effective  

528
00:45:06,160 --> 00:45:10,080
way to get out all this knowledge. And this is 
just a really simple way of getting that idea.

529
00:45:10,080 --> 00:45:14,320
It's funny because when I talk about this, I get 
that reaction a lot where people are like, "Well,  

530
00:45:14,320 --> 00:45:18,560
doesn't it feel coercive?" And I'm like, "Well, 
you got to go in pure of heart." You've got to  

531
00:45:18,560 --> 00:45:24,000
go in open to being wrong and even expected to 
be wrong. And you have to make that clear to  

532
00:45:24,000 --> 00:45:28,480
them. Right? If you're coming in and you're 
like, "Here's what I think. You agree? You  

533
00:45:28,480 --> 00:45:32,000
agree?" Of course you're not getting the answer 
you want. Or you might get the answer you want,  

534
00:45:32,000 --> 00:45:36,640
I might get a yes. If your goal is to get 
to yes, that's not what I'm talking about. 

535
00:45:36,640 --> 00:45:41,200
If your goal is to understand and you are coming 
from a, "Help me understand how I'm wrong,  

536
00:45:41,200 --> 00:45:45,600
help me understand what I'm getting wrong here" 
and approach it with that sort of curiosity and  

537
00:45:45,600 --> 00:45:50,560
humility and make sure that you're caring yourself 
and presenting yourself to this person in a way  

538
00:45:50,560 --> 00:45:57,200
that shows that, that you're not coming in hostile 
or forceful or something. Yeah. Because there are  

539
00:45:57,200 --> 00:46:00,960
absolutely circumstances where you're doing that 
and you're going to get bad intel because you're  

540
00:46:00,960 --> 00:46:04,560
making the person uncomfortable, so they're 
going to lie to you. But that's I think,  

541
00:46:04,560 --> 00:46:08,640
a whole set of interpersonal skill that we 
probably don't have time to talk about today.

542
00:46:09,200 --> 00:46:13,520
I wanted to come back to, you said this 
interesting insight about your CO that  

543
00:46:13,520 --> 00:46:19,040
he wanted to build something that felt 
like the future. I just wanted to share,  

544
00:46:19,040 --> 00:46:24,080
there's a story that has always stuck with me 
at Airbnb. There was a big launch coming up and  

545
00:46:24,080 --> 00:46:30,000
there was a designer sitting late in the office 
trying to update the website to include this new  

546
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:36,160
product. It was a launch of Airbnb Neighborhoods, 
I don't know, 10 years ago. And she was just like,  

547
00:46:36,160 --> 00:46:38,960
"Hey, Joe." And this is Joe Gebbia was walking 
around the office. And she's like, "Hey Joe,  

548
00:46:40,160 --> 00:46:42,400
what do you want the website to be?
